T*
(different kinds of numbers, like integers, floats, and doubles \(it was a C++ course\). ?You) Tj
T*
(mean, when I assign a variable, I have to say up front what kind of number this is?? It was) Tj
T*
(such an odd concept to me. A number is a number. Why do I have to say it?s this kind of number) Tj
T*
(or that kind of number? I dropped out of that class. A few years later, I decided I wanted to) Tj
T*
(try programming again. So I took another intro class. This time they were teaching with Python) Tj
T*
(instead of C++, so you can imagine my excitement to learn that I didn?t have to think of) Tj
T*
(numbers in this way anymore! It felt like the computer was meeting me partway. Over time, I) Tj
T*
(came to learn how pedantic computers are. They require a kind of exacting precision in saying) Tj
T*
(what you want them to do. And they?ll only ever do exactly what you tell them to do, nothing) Tj
T*
(more, nothing less. If there was a bug in your program, that wasn?t because the computer was) Tj
T*
(doing something you told it not to. The computer was only ever doing exactly what you told it) Tj
T*
(to do. A ?bug? was very likely a flaw in your conception of how the program should...) Tj
